{
  "doc_id": "40313",
  "text": "Alternative substrates or effects of NUDT2 disruption. Other in vitro substrates for NUDT2 whose levels might be affected by its loss include Ap 5 A, Ap [CITATION_1] A, other homodinucleoside polyphosphates with four or more phosphoryl groups, e.g. diguanosine tetraphosphate (Gp 4 G) [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , inorganic polyphosphate [CITATION_4] and phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate [CITATION_5] , but there is no evidence to suggest that these are significant substrates in vivo [CITATION_6] . Ap 5 A and Ap 6 A appear to be confined to secretory granules in certain specialized cells while no specific mechanisms are known for the synthesis of Gp 4 G and other homodinucleoside polyphosphates in mammalian cells [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Heterodinucleoside polyphosphates such as Ap 4 G and Ap 4 U can also be synthesized by aminoacyl-tRNA synthetases and, if present, would be detected by our luminometric assay and included as part of the 'Ap 4 A' pool, but as no unique functions have been ascribed to these molecules they are usually considered under the heading 'Ap 4 A' [CITATION_9] .",
